{
  "title": "Living an Eco-Friendly Lifestyle",
  "transcript": "Hi there, come on in. I'm Jessica Parker and I live right here in Baltimore, Maryland. It's very important for me to make sure I protect the environment because it's important for the future of our children. And they are the ones who have to live on this planet after we're gone. It is our duty to make minimal use of energy resources, to consume as little as we can, so that we leave the earth in good condition for the next generation, and they can benefit from clean air and water. We need to produce quite a lot of our own food because it is a better way of protecting the environment. By growing the food ourselves, we don't waste fuel on food transport from the supplier to the supermarket. In America, the food we eat at dinner may have traveled almost 2,000 miles. It obviously has a great impact on the environment, especially when the food has to travel such a long distance. We also keep chickens on our own, which also helps remain self-sufficient. However, our diet is mostly vegetarian. We get protein primarily through the eggs our chickens produce. In total, we've got seven chickens. They provide us with all our eggs and are always more productive during warmer seasons. Right now, they don't lay as many eggs as they do in summer, and we only get about 5 eggs each morning. We also have solar panels in the garden to produce our own energy, and when the sun is strong, we can power our house without using electricity from the grid. During the winter months, we have to rely on the grid for our energy supply. So much of the energy in this country comes from fossil fuels, and this obviously causes pollution. Our house isn't big. We only have four bedrooms with six people sharing the house. Living in smaller accommodation is another way to reduce energy waste.[cite: 8]",
